  "text": "BH Mass Estimate. The results of observations for Mrk 266 with the Spitzer, Hubble, GALEX, Chandra, and XMMNewton space telescopes are presented in [CITATION_1] . The relationship between H-band bulge luminosity and the mass of the nuclear black hole [CITATION_2] (Group 1 Galaxies) provides BH estimates of 2.3 × 10 8 and 2.6 × 10 8 ⊙ for Mrk 266 SW and NE, respectively, where the scatter is 0.3 in log. The luminosity of high ionization, mid-infrared emission lines can also be used to estimate MBH using relationships derived by [CITATION_3] . The differences arise from the wide scatter in calibrating BH versus luminosity or velocity dispersion. Also, there is no similar infrared spectral observation for Mrk261/262. Therefore, we are going to estimate the black hole masses in the same way from our optical spectra of Mrk261/262 and Mrk 266 [CITATION_4] , using the width of the [OIII] 5007 line. Note that a tight correlation exists for active galaxies between the velocity dispersion * of the bulge in a galaxy and the mass of its nuclear black hole BH [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Moreover, many groups have used the width of the [OIII] 5007 line as a substitute for the stellar velocity dispersion * of galaxy bulges. So, at The BH / ⊙ - * relation on logarithmic scales for 17 objects from [CITATION_7] . The solid line is the best fits to data of samples.",
